<DOC><DOCNO> SJMN91-06348237 </DOCNO><ACCESS> 06348237 </ACCESS><DESCRIPT>  BRIEF; PROFESSIONAL; BASEBALL  </DESCRIPT><LEADPARA>  Pittsburgh has lost Bobby Bonilla and apparently will be unable to keep BarryBonds much longer, but at least the Pirates are hanging on to Steve Buechele.;  The third baseman agreed to an $11 million, four-year deal with the Pirateson Thursday.  </LEADPARA><SECTION>  Sports  </SECTION><HEADLINE>  PIRATES HOLD ON TO BUECHELE, GET BAD NEWS ABOUTBONDSBRAVES RE-SIGN NIXON  </HEADLINE><MEMO>  Baseball Notebook  </MEMO><TEXT>     As for Bonds, agent Rod Wright told the Pirates on Thursday there is nochance of any long-term contract being worked out between the two sides.Bonds' contract with the Pirates has a year left.;   &quot;He said he saw no wayBarry would be willing to commit himself with what the market is out there,&quot;Pirates General Manager Larry Doughty.;   Bonds expects to receive at least$30 million over five years when he becomes a free agent after next season.;  The Pirates acquired Buechele, 30, from Texas in August in the midst of theirdrive to a second consecutive National League East championship. Buecheledrove in 66 runs for the Rangers and 18 for the Pirates in 1990.; NIXON STAYSPUT: Otis Nixon, suspended for cocaine use during the Atlanta Braves' pennantdrive, re-signed with the team, saying he was spurning a richer offer from theCalifornia Angels to stay in Atlanta.;   Nixon and the Braves agreed on atwo-year contract with a third year at his option -- a deal similar instructure to one reportedly offered by the Angels. The two-year deal is set at$5.6 million, with the option year bringing the value to a possible $8.1million.;   &quot;I took less money to come back with the Braves,&quot; Nixon said,adding, &quot;I never wanted to leave the city.&quot;;   Nixon, acquired from Montreallast April, set a franchise record with 72 stolen bases and hit .297, 69points above his lifetime average. But on Sept. 16, Commissioner Fay Vincentsuspended him for 60 days after he failed a drug test.; ETC.: Ken Keltner, 75,the Cleveland Indians third baseman who gained fame for stopping JoeDiMaggio's 56-game hitting streak with two good fielding plays in 1941, died,apparently of a heart attack, in New Berlin, Wis. . . . Boston Red Sox pitcherRoger Clemens was found innocent of a misdemeanor charge stemming from analleged barroom brawl with an off-duty police officer in Houston in January. .. . Outfielder Dan Pasqua of the Chicago White Sox will submit to random urinetests under an agreement that could lead to dismissal of minor drug chargesagainst him in New Jersey. Pasqua was arrested in October after police weretipped off that a package addressed to Pasqua contained marijuana. . . .Former A's pitcher Eric Plunk, 28, released last month by the New YorkYankees, agreed to a minor league contract with the Toronto Blue Jays.  </TEXT><BYLINE>  Mercury News Wire Services  </BYLINE><COUNTRY>  USA  </COUNTRY><EDITION>  Morning Final  </EDITION><CODE>  SJ  </CODE><NAME>  San Jose Mercury News  </NAME><PUBDATE>   911213  </PUBDATE> <DAY>  Friday  </DAY><MONTH>  December  </MONTH><PG.COL>  13E  </PG.COL><PUBYEAR>  1991  </PUBYEAR><REGION>  WEST  </REGION><STATE>  CA  </STATE><WORD.CT>  459  </WORD.CT><DATELINE>  Friday, December 13, 199100348237,SJ1  </DATELINE><COPYRGHT>  Copyright 1991, San Jose Mercury News  </COPYRGHT><LIMLEN>  1  </LIMLEN><LANGUAGE>  ENG  </LANGUAGE></DOC>